\begin{document}

\title{A Hybrid Approach to Real-Time Email Spam Detection using Machine Learning, Heuristic Trigger Analysis, and Browser-Level DOM Injection}

\author{
\IEEEauthorblockN{Prof. Vaneeta Kshirsagar}
\IEEEauthorblockA{\textit{Dr. D. Y. Patil Institute of Technology} \\
Pimpri, Pune, India}
\and
\IEEEauthorblockN{Rahul Borana}
\IEEEauthorblockA{\textit{Dr. D. Y. Patil Institute of Technology} \\
Pimpri, Pune, India}
\and
\IEEEauthorblockN{Manish Jaiswal}
\IEEEauthorblockA{\textit{Dr. D. Y. Patil Institute of Technology} \\
Pimpri, Pune, India}
}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Spam is genuinely infuriating---not just because it clogs inboxes, but because a single phishing email can compromise an entire organisation. Nearly half of all email traffic today is unsolicited bulk mail, costing businesses billions yearly, and the filters most people rely on have a significant blind spot: they analyse text in isolation, completely ignoring the context of the mail client the user is actually sitting in front of. This paper describes Smart Spam Detector, a classification system built around three fused signals rather than a single model. We combined a Multinomial Naive Bayes classifier with a deterministic trigger-word scanner and live Gmail UI signals, then shipped the whole thing as a Manifest V3 Chrome extension that injects a result overlay directly into Gmail's Document Object Model. To keep the backend small enough for cheap serverless hosting, we dropped heavy NLP libraries entirely and wrote a lightweight regex preprocessor instead, using TF-IDF features capped at 5{,}000 dimensions. Training on a merged corpus of over 38{,}000 emails drawn from the UCI SMS Spam Collection and the Enron Email Corpus, an 80--20 split gave us 96.68\% accuracy, 97\% precision, and 96\% recall. What mattered more to us than that headline number, though, was cutting false negatives---the missed spam that actually reaches users. Our hybrid scoring engine overrides weak model predictions whenever trigger-word density crosses calibrated thresholds or Gmail's own UI signals a warning, reducing false negatives by 70.4\% in targeted testing. The Flask backend responds in single-digit milliseconds, the extension handles Gmail's obfuscated SPA layout through four redundant DOM extraction strategies, and the whole system stays light enough to run indefinitely on a free hosting tier.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Email Spam Detection, Machine Learning, Multinomial Naive Bayes, TF-IDF, Heuristic Analysis, Chrome Extension, Gmail DOM Injection, Hybrid Classification, Natural Language Processing, Browser Security.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

Email has been the backbone of online communication for over three decades. Its open, decentralised design is largely what made the internet what it is---but that same openness is what spammers exploit. The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol was never built with sender verification in mind, so flooding millions of inboxes costs almost nothing. Today, spam accounts for roughly 45\% of all global email traffic \cite{b1}. Beyond the obvious annoyance of wasted storage, spam is a genuine security threat. Phishing campaigns and social engineering attacks arrive daily, dressed up to look like account alerts or business correspondence, trying to harvest credentials or push malware.

Researchers have been attacking this problem for decades. Early filters used blacklists, keyword matching, and header inspection. Spammers adapted fast---they started obfuscating words, embedding messages inside images, and cycling through fresh domains. That arms race is what brought machine learning into the picture. Naive Bayes classifiers became a kind of default baseline because they are fast, easy to train, and surprisingly effective on text despite their mathematically na\"{i}ve independence assumption \cite{b2}.

The trouble with most published work, though, is that it treats spam detection as a static text classification problem. Feed a string in, get a label back, done. That framing ignores the actual environment users work in. When someone opens an email in Gmail, their browser already knows things a backend model never will: is this message sitting in the spam folder? Is Gmail rendering a red phishing warning banner above it? What does the sender's display name look like? Academic benchmarks never touch these signals because they operate entirely offline.

There is also a serious gap between what gets published and what can realistically be deployed. Transformer models like BERT \cite{b3} push impressive numbers on static test sets, but running a multi-gigabyte model inside a real-time browser extension is not practical---latency suffers, hosting costs jump, and the user experience degrades. A browser extension has to respond in well under a second or users simply stop clicking it.

Smart Spam Detector was our attempt to close both of those gaps at once. Rather than scaling up to a heavier model, we combined three types of signals inside a single scoring engine:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Signal 1 --- Statistical Model Probability:} The raw posterior from a Multinomial Naive Bayes classifier trained on TF-IDF features from the merged SMS and Enron corpus.
    \item \textbf{Signal 2 --- Heuristic Trigger-Words:} A deterministic scan against 70 curated spam phrases using strict word-boundary matching to avoid partial-word false alarms.
    \item \textbf{Signal 3 --- Gmail Client Signals:} Real-time flags read directly from Gmail's live DOM by the Chrome extension---native spam-folder placement, phishing banners, and sender metadata.
\end{itemize}

These three signals are fused in the Flask backend. When the model incorrectly classifies a politely-worded phishing email as clean, the trigger-word engine or a Gmail folder flag can override that call. This specifically targets false negatives, which are the worst failure mode in a spam filter---one missed phishing email can be catastrophic for an individual user or an organisation.

Equally critical was how we delivered the tool. The extension works \textit{inside} Gmail without asking users to copy-paste anything. Our content script injects a button directly into the email view; clicking it extracts the text and fires off a classification request, with the result displayed as an overlay in the same tab. Because Gmail is a heavily obfuscated Single Page Application that periodically reshuffles its CSS classes, we wrote four redundant DOM extraction strategies so the extension survives minor UI changes without breaking.

The rest of this paper is organised as follows. Section~II covers the mathematical foundations. Section~III formalises the problem. Section~IV reviews the relevant prior work. Section~V analyses computational complexity. Section~VI describes the methodology, Section~VII the implementation, and Section~VIII reports experimental results. Section~IX discusses limitations and Section~X concludes with future directions.

\section{Theoretical Foundations of Spam Classification}

Spam detection is fundamentally a binary classification task. Given an email $E$, we want to assign it to one of two classes: $C \in \{spam, ham\}$. The mathematical tools we draw on come from probability theory, information retrieval, and computational linguistics.

\subsection{Bayesian Classification Framework}

Naive Bayes computes the posterior probability of each class from the words present in the document. Treating the email as a bag of words $\mathbf{x} = (x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_d)$, Bayes' theorem gives us:

\begin{equation}
P(c \mid \mathbf{x}) = \frac{P(c) \cdot P(\mathbf{x} \mid c)}{P(\mathbf{x})}
\end{equation}

To make this tractable, we assume conditional independence between words given the class---the ``naive'' part:

\begin{equation}
P(\mathbf{x} \mid c) = \prod_{i=1}^{d} P(x_i \mid c)
\end{equation}

Classification then reduces to picking the highest-scoring class:

\begin{equation}
\hat{c} = \arg\max_{c \in \{spam, ham\}} P(c) \cdot \prod_{i=1}^{d} P(x_i \mid c)
\end{equation}

The conditional independence assumption is obviously false---``bank'' and ``account'' co-occur constantly---but the classifier still works well in practice. The reason, as Rish explains \cite{b4}, is that exact probability estimates are not required; only the \textit{ranking} between classes needs to be correct. Since the independence violation tends to bias estimates for both classes in the same direction, the final decision usually stays correct.

\subsection{Multinomial Event Model}

We chose the Multinomial Naive Bayes model over the Multivariate Bernoulli variant \cite{b5}. The Bernoulli model only records whether a word is present or absent in a document. The Multinomial model counts occurrences, which matters for email---spammers deliberately repeat high-value keywords like ``free'' or ``win'' to grab attention, and ignoring those counts throws away useful signal. Conditional probability for term $t$ in class $c$ is estimated using Laplace-smoothed maximum likelihood:

\begin{equation}
P(t \mid c) = \frac{count(t, c) + \alpha}{\sum_{t' \in V} count(t', c) + \alpha \cdot |V|}
\end{equation}

where $\alpha = 1$ is the smoothing parameter, $V$ is the vocabulary, and $count(t, c)$ is the frequency of term $t$ in class-$c$ documents.

\subsection{TF-IDF Feature Representation}

Raw word counts have a well-known problem: stop words like ``the'' and ``is'' appear everywhere and drown out the words that actually matter. TF-IDF \cite{b6} addresses this by weighting each word's frequency against how rare it is across the corpus:

\begin{equation}
\text{TF-IDF}(t, d, D) = \text{TF}(t, d) \times \log\frac{|D|}{|\{d' \in D : t \in d'\}|}
\end{equation}

The IDF term automatically downweights universal filler words while amplifying terms that concentrate in a small subset of documents. For spam, this naturally surfaces domain-specific signals---words like ``lottery,'' ``wire,'' or ``inheritance'' jump in weight precisely because they are rare in legitimate email.

\subsection{Heuristic Classification and Rule-Based Systems}

Before statistical models took over, anti-spam tools were essentially large sets of handcrafted rules. Systems like SpamAssassin assigned a weighted penalty score to each matched pattern; if the total crossed a threshold, the email was flagged \cite{b7}. Rule-based systems degrade fast when spammers change their vocabulary, but they have two genuine advantages: they are fully transparent, and they let practitioners inject immediate domain knowledge that a statistical model may not pick up from training data alone.

This is the core motivation for our hybrid design. We did not discard rule-based reasoning---we used deterministic trigger-word checks to audit and, where necessary, override the statistical model's predictions.

