\subsection{Data Engineering and Corpus Construction}

Building a model that actually generalises required combining sources with meaningfully different writing styles. We used two datasets:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{UCI SMS Spam Collection:} 5{,}574 SMS messages. SMS spam shares a lot of linguistic DNA with email spam---fake prize announcements, urgent calls to action, suspicious links---so including it adds stylistic diversity.
    \item \textbf{Enron Email Corpus:} Approximately 33{,}000 real business emails from the Enron archives. These gave our ham class a solid grounding in how professional correspondence actually reads.
\end{enumerate}

Combining the two involved standardising column names to a consistent \texttt{label}/\texttt{text} schema, converting numeric labels to strings, dropping duplicate entries, and shuffling with a fixed random seed before training.

\subsection{Lightweight Text Preprocessing}

One deliberate choice we made early on was to avoid large NLP libraries entirely. NLTK, SpaCy, and similar packages carry significant weight---that bloat becomes a real problem on free-tier cloud platforms where slug size affects cold-start time and available RAM. Email spam classification also does not need deep syntactic parsing or named entity recognition; clean tokenisation is enough.

The custom preprocessor we wrote runs three operations:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Lowercase conversion:} Eliminates capitalisation variance without losing any information.
    \item \textbf{Regex cleaning:} The pattern \texttt{[{\textasciicircum}a-z\textbackslash s]} strips digits, punctuation, URLs, and stray symbols in a single pass.
    \item \textbf{Stopword removal:} A Python \texttt{set} of 50 high-frequency English words enables $O(1)$ lookup per token during filtering.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Lightweight Text Preprocessing Pipeline}
\label{alg:preprocess}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\REQUIRE $text$: Raw email string
\REQUIRE $StopSet$: Curated set of 50 stopwords
\STATE $text \leftarrow \text{lowercase}(text)$
\STATE $text \leftarrow \text{regex\_sub}(\texttt{[{\textasciicircum}a-z\textbackslash s]}, \text{' '}, text)$
\STATE $text \leftarrow \text{normalize\_whitespace}(text)$
\STATE $words \leftarrow \text{split}(text)$
\STATE $words \leftarrow [w \mid w \in words \land w \notin StopSet]$
\RETURN $\text{join}(words)$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The result is a stopword-free, lowercase token string produced in $O(n)$ time with no external dependencies.

\subsection{Feature Extraction and Model Training}

Preprocessed text is fed to scikit-learn's \texttt{TfidfVectorizer} with \texttt{max\_features=5000}. Capping the vocabulary reduces the serialised model size and serves as implicit regularisation against rare, overfitted terms.

We trained scikit-learn's \texttt{MultinomialNB} on an 80--20 stratified split. Both the fitted vectorizer and the trained classifier are serialised together using Python's \texttt{pickle} module, so the Flask server loads them once at startup and keeps them in memory for the lifetime of the process. Retraining on the fly is never required.

\subsection{Hybrid Scoring Engine}

The hybrid engine sits between the Naive Bayes output and the API response. Its job is to catch cases where the statistical model was misled---typically by phishing emails written in deliberately polite or professional language---and correct the prediction using the additional signals we have available.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Hybrid Scoring Engine}
\label{alg:hybrid}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\REQUIRE $P_{spam}, P_{ham}$: Model posterior probabilities
\REQUIRE $\tau$: Trigger word count
\REQUIRE $\delta$: Trigger density (\%)
\REQUIRE $g$: Gmail spam flag (boolean)
\STATE $pred \leftarrow$ \textbf{if} $P_{spam} > P_{ham}$ \textbf{then} $spam$ \textbf{else} $ham$
\STATE $conf \leftarrow \max(P_{spam}, P_{ham})$
\IF{$g = True$ \textbf{and} $pred = ham$ \textbf{and} $P_{ham} < 0.92$}
    \STATE $pred \leftarrow spam$
    \STATE $conf \leftarrow \min(\max(P_{spam} + 0.30, 0.75), 0.98)$
\ENDIF
\IF{$pred = ham$ \textbf{and} $\tau \geq 2$}
    \STATE $boost \leftarrow \min(\tau \times 0.08, 0.45)$
    \IF{$\tau \geq 4$ \textbf{or} ($\tau \geq 3$ \textbf{and} $P_{spam} > 0.10$) \textbf{or} ($\tau \geq 2$ \textbf{and} $P_{spam} > 0.25$) \textbf{or} $\delta > 2.5$}
        \STATE $pred \leftarrow spam$
        \STATE $conf \leftarrow \min(P_{spam} + boost, 0.98)$
    \ENDIF
\ENDIF
\RETURN $(pred, conf)$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The cascade ordering matters. Gmail context flags come first because they reflect server-side intelligence---IP reputation checks, SPF/DKIM validation---that we cannot replicate in the browser. Trigger density checks follow. The boost values and thresholds were determined through iterative testing on held-out emails rather than derived analytically.

\subsubsection{Trigger-Word Detection with Word Boundaries}

A small but important implementation detail: all trigger matching uses strict word-boundary anchors (\texttt{\textbackslash b}). Without this, a word like ``freedom'' would falsely match the trigger ``free,'' generating spurious flags on ordinary text. With boundary-aware matching, only actual instances of phrases like ``verify account,'' ``lottery,'' or ``earn money'' count. Our trigger lexicon contains approximately 70 high-risk phrases selected based on domain knowledge and manual inspection of misclassified examples.


\section{Implementation and Deployment}

\subsection{Backend API Architecture}

The Flask microservice exposes two endpoints. \texttt{GET /} is a simple health check used by the extension's settings panel to show a live connection status indicator. \texttt{POST /predict} is the classification endpoint; it accepts a JSON payload containing \texttt{text}, a boolean \texttt{gmail\_spam}, and an optional \texttt{sender} string.

CORS is enabled globally so the extension can query the API from within Gmail tabs. In production, the application runs behind Gunicorn with pre-forked workers, which handles concurrent requests without per-request startup overhead.

\subsection{Chrome Extension Architecture}

The extension targets the Manifest V3 specification and is divided into three main components.

\subsubsection{Background Service Worker}

The service worker acts as a secure intermediary between the content script and the remote API. It listens for messages from the content script, retrieves the stored API URL from \texttt{chrome.storage.local}, makes the outbound \texttt{fetch} call to Flask, and relays the result back. Keeping network requests out of the content-script context is a Manifest V3 requirement, not just a design preference.

\subsubsection{Content Script and Gmail DOM Injection}

Gmail's SPA structure means there are no reliable page-load events to hook into. The content script runs a \texttt{setInterval} check every second to detect whether the user is currently viewing an email thread, and injects a floating ``Check Spam'' button when one is detected.

