Table~\ref{tab:fn_reduction} shows the results. The standalone Naive Bayes model missed 27 of the 200 emails---a 13.5\% false-negative rate on the adversarial set. Adding trigger-word boosting cut that to 14 misses. Layering in Gmail context signals brought it down further to 8, a 70.4\% total reduction in false negatives compared to the baseline. That improvement came from adding two deterministic layers on top of the same underlying statistical model, with no retraining required.

