\section{Problem Formulation}

\subsection{Input Representation}

We treat the raw email $E$ as an unstructured text string. A preprocessing function cleans this string and produces a token sequence:

\begin{equation}
E' = \text{preprocess}(E) = (w_1, w_2, \ldots, w_n)
\end{equation}

where preprocessing applies lowercasing, regex-based character stripping, whitespace normalisation, and stopword removal.

\subsection{Model Prediction Function}

The TF-IDF vectorizer maps $E'$ into a $d$-dimensional feature vector $\mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^d$ (with $d = 5000$). The Multinomial Naive Bayes classifier then produces class posteriors:

\begin{equation}
P_{spam} = P(spam \mid \mathbf{x}), \quad P_{ham} = P(ham \mid \mathbf{x})
\end{equation}

The base statistical prediction is:

\begin{equation}
\hat{y}_{model} =
\begin{cases}
spam, & \text{if } P_{spam} > P_{ham} \\
ham, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Trigger-Word Density Function}

Let $\mathcal{T}$ be the curated list of spam-indicative trigger phrases. We count matches using whole-word boundary regex on the lowercased email text:

\begin{equation}
\tau(E) = |\{t \in \mathcal{T} : \exists \text{ match of } \texttt{\\b} \cdot t \cdot \texttt{\\b} \text{ in } E_{lower}\}|
\end{equation}

Trigger density is then the fraction of total words that matched:

\begin{equation}
\delta(E) = \frac{\tau(E)}{\max(|E_{words}|, 1)} \times 100
\end{equation}

\subsection{Hybrid Override Function}

The final classification fuses all three signals through cascading override rules. Let $g$ denote whether the email is flagged in Gmail's spam folder (boolean). The decision logic is:

\begin{equation}
\hat{y}_{final} =
\begin{cases}
spam, & \text{if } g = True \land \hat{y}_{model} = ham \land P_{ham} < 0.92 \\
spam, & \text{if } \hat{y}_{model} = ham \land \tau(E) \geq 4 \\
spam, & \text{if } \hat{y}_{model} = ham \land \tau(E) \geq 3 \land P_{spam} > 0.10 \\
spam, & \text{if } \hat{y}_{model} = ham \land \tau(E) \geq 2 \land P_{spam} > 0.25 \\
spam, & \text{if } \hat{y}_{model} = ham \land \delta(E) > 2.5 \\
\hat{y}_{model}, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

When a heuristic override fires, the confidence score is adjusted using a bounded boost:

\begin{equation}
C_{adjusted} = \min(P_{spam} + \min(\tau(E) \times 0.08, \; 0.45), \; 0.98)
\end{equation}

The 98\% ceiling means the system never reports certainty on a heuristic call alone, which keeps the output honest. The cascade ordering ensures that strong environmental signals---like Gmail's own spam-folder placement---take precedence before trigger density checks are evaluated.

\subsection{Overall System Function}

The full pipeline can be written as a single composed function:

\begin{equation}
F(E, g) = \text{HybridOverride}(\text{NB}(\text{TFIDF}(\text{preprocess}(E))), \; \tau(E), \; g)
\end{equation}

This captures the complete chain: raw email goes through preprocessing, TF-IDF vectorisation, and Naive Bayes scoring, and those outputs are then passed into the hybrid override along with the trigger count and Gmail flag to produce the final label.


\section{Literature Review}

Spam filtering has a longer research history than most people realise---serious academic work on it dates back to the late 1990s---and the approaches have shifted considerably over that time.

\subsection{Early Statistical Approaches}

Sahami et al.\ \cite{b2} were among the first to demonstrate that a simple bag-of-words Naive Bayes classifier could catch spam reliably without elaborate linguistic rules. Their key insight was that spam has a distinctive vocabulary signature that separates it from legitimate mail fairly cleanly, even with a probability model that ignores word order. It was a foundational result because it showed that simple statistics could beat handcrafted rule systems on real corpora.

Building on that, Androutsopoulos et al.\ \cite{b8} introduced cost-sensitive evaluation metrics into the conversation. Treating a false positive and a false negative as equally bad misses the point: burying a legitimate email in the spam folder disrupts the user far more than letting a piece of junk slip through. Their work also showed that Naive Bayes holds up surprisingly well on small labelled datasets---relevant for real-world deployments where users will not manually label thousands of messages to personalise their filters.

\subsection{Event Model Comparisons}

McCallum and Nigam \cite{b5} compared the Multinomial and Multivariate Bernoulli event models for Naive Bayes text classification in detail. The Bernoulli model treats each word as a binary present-or-absent feature; the Multinomial model counts how many times each word appears. For longer documents the Multinomial model wins clearly, and for email spam the reason is intuitive: spammers deliberately repeat attention-grabbing terms, so word frequency carries genuine discriminative signal that the Bernoulli model discards entirely.

Metsis et al.\ \cite{b9} confirmed this specifically for spam by benchmarking five Naive Bayes variants across multiple corpora. Their finding that a boolean-transformed Multinomial variant performed best is actually what pointed us toward TF-IDF representation, which achieves a similar effect---downweighting universally common terms while lifting the rare, discriminative ones.

\subsection{Feature Engineering and Text Representation}

TF-IDF as a term-weighting scheme predates most modern spam research. Salton and Buckley \cite{b6} developed it for information retrieval in the late 1980s, but it transferred naturally to text classification because it aligns well with the intuition that rare, domain-specific words should carry more weight than frequent ones.

The question of vocabulary size has practical consequences. Keep too many features and the model overfits while consuming excess memory; keep too few and discriminative terms fall out. Prior work suggests that a TF-IDF vocabulary between 3{,}000 and 10{,}000 features is a reasonable range for spam classification \cite{b10}. We settled on 5{,}000 features---high enough to retain key signal, small enough that the serialised model loads in milliseconds on cheap hosting.

\subsection{Corpus Construction and the Enron Dataset}

Acquiring authentic labelled email data is genuinely difficult. Few people want to share their inbox for public research, and synthetic datasets look nothing like real correspondence. The Enron Email Corpus \cite{b11} is valuable precisely because it is real: released as part of the post-fraud investigation, it is one of the very few public collections of genuine business email, giving models a realistic view of professional communication patterns.

We combined the Enron data with the UCI SMS Spam Collection to expose the classifier to both formal business writing and the terse, urgent messaging style typical of SMS spam campaigns. The idea was to build a model that is not brittle toward either format.

\subsection{Browser-Based Security and Extension Architectures}

Deploying machine learning inside browser extensions is still a relatively niche area in the literature. Most spam filters operate server-side or inside dedicated mail clients. Chrome's Manifest V3 specification introduced meaningful security tightening---persistent background pages were replaced with short-lived service workers, and content security policies became stricter \cite{b12}---which complicates long-running tasks in extensions but also makes them safer for end users. These constraints reinforce the case for a lightweight remote microservice rather than running inference locally in the browser.

Gmail specifically is hard to parse because it is a heavily obfuscated Single Page Application. The DOM is constructed dynamically, CSS class names are minified and change between deployments, and the page structure shifts when Google iterates on the UI \cite{b13}. Any extraction strategy that relies on a single selector will eventually break; redundant fallbacks are not optional.

\subsection{Hybrid and Ensemble Approaches}

Hybrid systems that combine statistical models with rule-based reasoning have a solid track record. SpamAssassin \cite{b7} is the canonical example: it aggregates scores from hundreds of manual rules alongside a Naive Bayes model, with the weighted total determining the final verdict. Cormack's systematic review \cite{b10} found that hybrid approaches consistently outperform either pure machine learning or pure rule-based systems taken alone.

More recent ensemble approaches---Random Forests, SVMs, Gradient Boosting \cite{b14}---push accuracy numbers higher but at significant inference cost. Our design is different in intent: we are not stacking multiple heavyweight models. Instead, one fast statistical classifier is paired with a deterministic heuristic layer and live client-side context. The goal is the practical performance of an ensemble without the latency or hosting overhead.


\section{Computational Complexity Analysis}

For a system embedded in a browser extension, inference latency is not an academic concern---it is the main usability constraint. An overlay that takes three seconds to appear after a user clicks a button will not be used.

\subsection{Preprocessing Module Complexity}

For an email of $n$ characters, our preprocessor runs four steps:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Lowercasing: $O(n)$
    \item Regex symbol stripping: $O(n)$
    \item Whitespace normalisation: $O(n)$
    \item Stopword removal: Our stopword list is stored in a Python set, giving $O(1)$ lookup per token. For $m$ tokens this is $O(m)$.
\end{itemize}

The full preprocessing step therefore scales as:

\begin{equation}
T_{preprocess} = O(n)
\end{equation}

\subsection{Feature Extraction Complexity}

Transforming $m$ tokens into TF-IDF features against a vocabulary of size $d = 5000$:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Vocabulary hash-map lookups over tokens: $O(m)$
    \item IDF weight application: $O(d)$
\end{itemize}

Since $d$ is a fixed constant, vectorisation complexity is simply:

\begin{equation}
T_{vectorize} = O(m)
\end{equation}

\subsection{Classification Complexity}

Multinomial Naive Bayes computes log-posteriors for two classes by summing log-probabilities over the $d$-dimensional feature vector:

\begin{equation}
T_{classify} = O(d) = O(5000) = O(1)
\end{equation}

Because $d$ is fixed at model training time, inference time is constant regardless of email length.

\subsection{Heuristic Trigger Scan Complexity}

The trigger scan applies regex word-boundary matching for each of the $|\mathcal{T}| \approx 70$ phrases against the input text:

\begin{equation}
T_{trigger} = O(|\mathcal{T}| \times n) = O(n)
\end{equation}

\subsection{End-to-End Complexity}

Summing all pipeline stages:

\begin{equation}
T_{total} = O(n) + O(m) + O(1) + O(n) = O(n)
\end{equation}

The entire pipeline runs in linear time with respect to the input length.

\subsection{Comparison with Alternative Approaches}

To place this in context:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{BERT / Transformer models:} $O(n^2)$ due to full self-attention over the sequence.
    \item \textbf{SVM with RBF kernel:} $O(n_{sv} \times d)$, scaling with the number of support vectors $n_{sv}$.
    \item \textbf{Random Forest:} $O(k \times d \times \log n_t)$ for $k$ trees over $n_t$ training examples.
    \item \textbf{Our system:} $O(n)$.
\end{itemize}

Linear time complexity is what allows the backend to respond in single-digit milliseconds, making the system practical inside a real-time browser extension.


\section{System Architecture and Methodology}

Smart Spam Detector is split into three decoupled components: a Flask-based prediction API, a Manifest V3 Chrome extension, and a Streamlit web dashboard. Keeping these separate meant we could develop, test, and redeploy each independently without risking the others.

