When the button is clicked, the text extraction engine tries four DOM strategies in sequence until one succeeds:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Strategy 1:} \texttt{div.a3s.aiL} or \texttt{div.a3s}---Gmail's primary message body container.
    \item \textbf{Strategy 2:} \texttt{.ii.gt}---an outer wrapper that survives some layout changes.
    \item \textbf{Strategy 3:} Elements containing \texttt{[data-message-id]} attributes.
    \item \textbf{Strategy 4:} The main content region inside \texttt{div[role=''main'']}.
\end{enumerate}

After extracting text, the script strips standard Gmail UI strings---``Reply,'' ``Forward,'' ``Report spam''---to prevent those from skewing classification. The email subject line is prepended to the body before the request is sent.

At the same time the text is extracted, the script reads the environment: it checks whether the URL path contains ``spam,'' looks for red phishing warning banners in the DOM, and reads any native Gmail labels on the message. These signals are bundled into the POST payload alongside the text.

\subsubsection{Popup Interface}

The popup provides a manual text scanner, a list of the last 20 scans persisted in \texttt{chrome.storage.local}, and a settings tab where users can override the Flask API URL. The interface uses a dark glassmorphism style with CSS gradients and smooth transitions.

\subsection{Streamlit Web Dashboard}

For users who do not want a browser extension, the Streamlit dashboard provides equivalent functionality through a web form. It renders colour-coded prediction cards, a confidence progress bar, trigger-word highlights, and a session scan counter. The dashboard loads the pickled model directly---it does not call the Flask API---so it operates with the base Naive Bayes scores without the hybrid override layer.


