\subsection{Case Study 1: Effective Spam Detection}

\textbf{Input:} ``Congratulations! You have been selected as the WINNER of our exclusive lottery. Click here to claim your FREE prize of \$1,000,000. Act now --- this offer expires TODAY!''

\textbf{Pipeline Execution:} A straightforward case. After preprocessing, the TF-IDF vectorizer heavily weighted terms like ``congratulations,'' ``winner,'' ``lottery,'' and ``prize.'' The Naive Bayes model predicted spam with near-certainty ($P_{spam} = 0.9987$). The trigger scan simultaneously matched 8 phrases, including ``winner,'' ``lottery,'' ``claim,'' and ``act now.'' Both the statistical and heuristic paths agreed. Final reported confidence: 99.87\%.

\subsection{Case Study 2: Hybrid Override in Action}

\textbf{Input:} ``Hi, I wanted to follow up on our conversation from the meeting. I think there's a great opportunity for both of us to earn significant income if we move quickly. I've attached the investment details. Let me know your thoughts!''

\textbf{Pipeline Execution:} This email is the kind that causes problems---professionally worded to bypass statistical filters, but pushing a questionable investment pitch. The Naive Bayes model was deceived by the polite tone and predicted ham with $P_{ham} = 0.72$ ($P_{spam} = 0.28$). However, the trigger scan found three matched phrases: ``opportunity,'' ``earn,'' and ``investment.'' With $\tau = 3$ and $P_{spam} = 0.28 > 0.10$, the hybrid override condition fired, flipping the prediction to spam with an adjusted confidence of 52\%. A phishing attempt the statistical model would have missed was caught.

\subsection{Case Study 3: Correct Ham Preservation}

\textbf{Input:} ``Please find attached the quarterly financial report. The board meeting is scheduled for next Tuesday at 2 PM. Let me know if you need any additional materials.''

\textbf{Pipeline Execution:} The model correctly classified this as ham with $P_{ham} = 0.9934$. Although ``financial'' appears in the text, it is not in the trigger lexicon---it shows up far too often in ordinary business email to be a reliable spam indicator. The trigger scan returned zero matches, no override conditions were triggered, and the email was left untouched. This confirms the system does not generate false positives on standard professional correspondence.

\subsection{Case Study 4: Gmail Context Override}

\textbf{Input:} A short, ambiguous message: ``Please review the attached document at your earliest convenience.'' The extension reported \texttt{gmail\_spam = True} because Gmail had placed the email in the spam folder.

\textbf{Pipeline Execution:} On text alone, the model leaned toward ham with $P_{ham} = 0.89$. No trigger words were found. But Gmail's folder placement is a strong signal---it reflects server-side checks like IP blacklisting and SPF/DKIM validation that the extension cannot replicate locally. Because $P_{ham} = 0.89 < 0.92$, the Gmail context override fired, reclassifying the email as spam with a confidence of 75\%. The email was correctly flagged by deferring to Gmail's infrastructure.


\section{Discussion, Error Analysis, and Limitations}

Our results make a fairly clear case that aggressive model scaling is not the only path to good spam detection. Fusing a simple Naive Bayes classifier with deterministic heuristics and browser-native signals produced a system that is fast, cheap to host, and meaningfully more accurate on adversarial examples than the statistical baseline alone. The 96.68\% overall accuracy is competitive with much heavier models in the literature, and the 70.4\% false-negative reduction came purely from the override layer, not from retraining or architectural changes to the model.

\subsection{Strengths}

Several design choices contributed specifically to the system's practical performance:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Small footprint:} Avoiding heavy NLP libraries kept the entire backend---model, vectorizer, and application code---under 10 MB. This makes scale-to-zero serverless deployment viable with negligible cold-start time.
    \item \textbf{Transparent decisions:} When the system flags an email, it reports the exact trigger phrases it matched. Users can see why the decision was made, which builds trust and makes it easier to identify false positives.
    \item \textbf{Borrowed intelligence:} Reading Gmail's DOM-level signals gives the extension indirect access to Google's server-side spam infrastructure---IP reputation databases, authentication checks---without needing to replicate that infrastructure ourselves.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Limitations and Error Analysis}

There are genuine limitations that need to be acknowledged.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Independence assumption:} Naive Bayes scores words independently. Phrases like ``wire transfer'' or ``verify account'' carry meaning as units, not as isolated words, and the model cannot capture that. A bigram or n-gram model would help here.
    \item \textbf{Static trigger lexicon:} The 70-phrase trigger list is fixed at deployment time. Spam vocabulary evolves quickly, and a static list will gradually become less effective unless it is periodically reviewed and updated.
    \item \textbf{Gmail DOM fragility:} Our four extraction strategies currently cover Gmail's DOM structure reliably. But Google redesigns Gmail's front-end periodically, and if class names or element roles change significantly, the extension will need an update before extraction works again.
    \item \textbf{English only:} The preprocessing pipeline, stopword list, and trigger lexicon were built entirely around English. Multilingual spam---which is increasingly common---is invisible to the current system.
    \item \textbf{Image-based spam:} The pipeline operates on text. An email whose message is embedded inside a JPEG will appear empty after extraction and pass through undetected.
    \item \textbf{Hand-tuned thresholds:} The override thresholds ($P_{ham} < 0.92$, $\tau \geq 2$, etc.) were calibrated on our local test sets. They may not transfer perfectly to every user's inbox distribution without retuning.
\end{itemize}


\section{Conclusion and Future Scope}

\subsection{Conclusion}

Smart Spam Detector started as an attempt to bridge two gaps that we kept running into in the spam-filtering literature: the contextual blindness of backend-only models and the impracticality of deploying heavy architectures in real user-facing tools. The result is a system that runs inside Gmail, responds in single-digit milliseconds on the backend, costs essentially nothing to host, and still cuts missed spam by over 70\% compared to a standard Naive Bayes baseline.

The contribution here is not the Naive Bayes model itself---that is well-understood technology---but the fusion architecture. Combining statistical posteriors with deterministic trigger-word rules and live client-side signals into a single lightweight pipeline gives a much better outcome than any of those three signals produces independently. The Gmail context override alone rescued a substantial number of politely-worded phishing emails that the statistical model consistently missed.

The broader implication is worth stating plainly: hybrid systems that incorporate environmental context can compete with much heavier pure-ML approaches for real-world security tasks, especially when deployment constraints favour speed and portability over model sophistication. This principle is not specific to email spam; it should generalise to other browser-integrated security tools.

\subsection{Future Scope}

Several improvements would address the current limitations directly:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Distilled transformer backbone:} Swapping the Naive Bayes model for a quantised DistilBERT would capture phrase-level context and word sense, improving performance on adversarial inputs without the latency penalty of full BERT.

    \item \textbf{Adaptive trigger lexicon:} When a user reports a missed spam email, the system could automatically analyse token frequencies in the missed text against the known ham distribution and propose additions to the trigger list, building a feedback-driven update mechanism.

    \item \textbf{Cross-browser support:} The extension currently targets Chrome. Manifest V3 has been adopted by Firefox as well, so adapting the background service worker for Firefox compatibility is a logical next step.

    \item \textbf{Multilingual preprocessing:} Adding a language-detection step before preprocessing would allow the system to load language-appropriate stopword lists and trigger lexicons, extending coverage to Spanish, Hindi, Arabic, and other widely-targeted languages.

    \item \textbf{OCR integration for image spam:} Running a lightweight OCR pass---Tesseract.js is a viable browser-compatible option---on embedded images before classification would close the gap on a category of spam the current pipeline cannot see.

    \item \textbf{On-device federated learning:} To avoid sending raw email text to any external server at all, a federated learning approach could fine-tune the classifier locally on the user's device, improving personalisation while preserving privacy.
\end{enumerate}


\begin{thebibliography}{00}

\bibitem{b1} Statista Research Department, ``Global spam volume as percentage of total e-mail traffic from 2007 to 2023,'' \textit{Statista}, 2023.

\bibitem{b2} M. Sahami, S. Dumais, D. Heckerman, and E. Horvitz, ``A Bayesian approach to filtering junk e-mail,'' in \textit{Proc. AAAI Workshop on Learning for Text Categorization}, 1998, pp. 55--62.

\bibitem{b3} J. Devlin, M.-W. Chang, K. Lee, and K. Toutanova, ``BERT: Pre-training of deep bidirectional transformers for language understanding,'' in \textit{Proc. NAACL-HLT}, 2019, pp. 4171--4186.

\bibitem{b4} I. Rish, ``An empirical study of the naive Bayes classifier,'' in \textit{Proc. IJCAI Workshop on Empirical Methods in AI}, 2001, pp. 41--46.

\bibitem{b5} A. McCallum and K. Nigam, ``A comparison of event models for naive Bayes text classification,'' in \textit{Proc. AAAI Workshop on Learning for Text Categorization}, 1998, pp. 41--48.

\bibitem{b6} G. Salton and C. Buckley, ``Term-weighting approaches in automatic text retrieval,'' \textit{Information Processing and Management}, vol. 24, no. 5, pp. 513--523, 1988.

\bibitem{b7} J. Mason, ``Filtering spam with SpamAssassin,'' in \textit{Proc. USENIX Annual Technical Conference, FREENIX Track}, 2004.

\bibitem{b8} I. Androutsopoulos, J. Koutsias, K. V. Chandrinos, and C. D. Spyropoulos, ``An evaluation of naive Bayesian anti-spam filtering,'' in \textit{Proc. Workshop on Machine Learning in the New Information Age}, 2000, pp. 9--17.

\bibitem{b9} V. Metsis, I. Androutsopoulos, and G. Paliouras, ``Spam filtering with naive Bayes -- which naive Bayes?'' in \textit{Proc. CEAS}, 2006.

