\subsection{Lightweight Text Preprocessing}

One deliberate choice we made early on was to avoid large NLP libraries entirely. NLTK, SpaCy, and similar packages carry significant weight---that bloat becomes a real problem on free-tier cloud platforms where slug size affects cold-start time and available RAM. Email spam classification also does not need deep syntactic parsing or named entity recognition; clean tokenisation is enough.

The custom preprocessor we wrote runs three operations:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Lowercase conversion:} Eliminates capitalisation variance without losing any information.
    \item \textbf{Regex cleaning:} The pattern \texttt{[{\textasciicircum}a-z\textbackslash s]} strips digits, punctuation, URLs, and stray symbols in a single pass.
    \item \textbf{Stopword removal:} A Python \texttt{set} of 66 high-frequency English words enables $O(1)$ lookup per token during filtering.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Lightweight Text Preprocessing Pipeline}
\label{alg:preprocess}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\REQUIRE $text$: Raw email string
\REQUIRE $StopSet$: Curated set of 66 stopwords
\STATE $text \leftarrow \text{lowercase}(text)$
\STATE $text \leftarrow \text{regex\_sub}(\texttt{[{\textasciicircum}a-z\textbackslash s]}, \text{' '}, text)$
\STATE $text \leftarrow \text{normalize\_whitespace}(text)$
\STATE $words \leftarrow \text{split}(text)$
\STATE $words \leftarrow [w \mid w \in words \land w \notin StopSet]$
\RETURN $\text{join}(words)$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The result is a stopword-free, lowercase token string produced in $O(n)$ time with no external dependencies.

