Table~\ref{tab:baseline_metrics} shows the baseline numbers. Overall accuracy reached 96.68\%, with spam precision at 0.95 and ham recall at 0.98. The asymmetry is notable: the model is marginally more cautious about labelling something spam than it is about labelling something ham. In practice this is a desirable property---falsely burying a legitimate email is more disruptive for a user than letting occasional spam through---but it does mean the model has a higher false-negative rate on spam, which is what the hybrid engine is there to address.

\subsection{Hybrid System Impact on False Negatives}

We built a separate evaluation set of 200 spam emails written in deliberately polished, professional language---the kind that bypasses naive keyword detectors. This is the failure mode the hybrid engine was specifically designed for.

